14.4 WHICH TEMPLATE TO USE?
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TASK                          | USE THIS
------------------------------|----------------------------------
Summarize text                | Summarize Template
Explain a concept             | Explain in Simple Terms Template
Improve writing               | Rewrite/Improve Template
Generate ideas                | Generate Ideas Template
Explain code                  | Explain Code Template
Fix a bug                     | Debug an Error Template
Write new code                | Write New Code Template
Refactor code                 | Refactor Code Template
Generate an image             | Image Generation Formula
Make a decision               | Comparison/Decision Template
Not sure / complex task       | Universal Template


================================================================================
SECTION 15: THE GOLDEN RULES
================================================================================

1. STRUCTURE   -> Use XML tags or delimiters
2. SPECIFICITY -> Quantify everything, no vague words
3. TONE        -> Write how you want the output to sound
4. POSITIVE    -> Say what to do, not what to avoid
5. ITERATE     -> First draft is rarely perfect, refine it
6. CONTEXT     -> More background = better answers
7. EXAMPLES    -> Few-shot prompting when format matters
8. ESCAPE HATCH-> Let AI say "I don't know" vs. hallucinating


================================================================================
SECTION 16: COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
================================================================================

MISTAKE                          | FIX
---------------------------------|---------------------------------------------
Vague verbs ("look at this")     | Use specific verbs (analyze, debug, refactor)
No format specified              | Always say: table, bullets, code only, etc.
No audience specified            | Add "for a junior dev" or "for a manager"
Assuming AI knows context        | Provide background explicitly
Not specifying language/version  | Always say "Python 3.11" or "Java 17"
Negative constraints only        | Say what TO do, not just what NOT to do
No escape hatch for unknowns     | Add "If unsure, say 'I don't know'"
One giant prompt                 | Break complex tasks into steps


================================================================================
SECTION 17: SENIOR ENGINEER PROMPT TEMPLATE
================================================================================

Combine keywords from multiple categories for powerful prompts:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Act as a [ROLE].
 Write a [TASK] that is [QUALITY KEYWORD].
 Ensure it handles [DATA KEYWORD] and uses [SECURITY KEYWORD].
 Output as [FORMAT]."
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Full Template:
--------------
Act as a [SENIOR ROLE].

[TASK VERB] a [COMPONENT] that [DOES WHAT].

Architecture:
- Follow [PATTERN: Clean Architecture / Microservices / Event-driven]
- Apply [PRINCIPLES: SOLID / DRY / 12-Factor]

Quality Requirements:
- Make it [QUALITY: production-ready / robust / idempotent]
- Use [STYLE: idiomatic / modern] [LANGUAGE] syntax
- Handle [SAFETY: edge cases / race conditions / null inputs]

Security:
- Apply [SECURITY: Least Privilege / input validation / sanitization]
- Check against [STANDARD: OWASP Top 10]

Output:
- Include [DOCS: comments / docstrings / Mermaid diagram]
- Add [TESTS: unit tests / happy path / edge cases]


Example:
--------
Act as a Senior Backend Engineer.

Design an API endpoint that handles user registration.

Architecture:
- Follow Clean Architecture with separate domain and infrastructure layers
- Apply SOLID principles

Quality Requirements:
- Make it production-ready with proper error handling and logging
- Use idiomatic Python with type hints
- Handle edge cases (duplicate emails, invalid input, rate limiting)

Security:
- Apply input validation and sanitization
- Check against OWASP Top 10 (especially injection attacks)

Output:
- Include docstrings and inline comments
- Add unit tests for happy path and edge cases
- Generate a Mermaid sequence diagram of the registration flow


================================================================================
SECTION 18: REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE - BUG ANALYSIS PROMPT
================================================================================

BAD PROMPT:
"Look at this error and tell me what's wrong."

GOOD PROMPT:

<context>
I'm debugging a production issue in our Java Spring Boot application.
The audience for this analysis is the backend team.
</context>

<task>
Analyze the stack trace below. Identify:
1. The root cause of the exception
2. The exact line/method where it originates
3. Two potential fixes ranked by implementation effort
</task>

<stack_trace>
[paste your stack trace here]
</stack_trace>

<format>
- Use a numbered list for the 3 items above
- Keep each point under 50 words
- Include code snippets for the fixes
</format>


================================================================================
END OF COMPLETE PROMPT ENGINEERING GUIDE
================================================================================

TIP: USE THE TECHNICAL TERM
If you know the concept name (Mutex, Circuit Breaker, Memoization),
use it. The AI will instantly treat you as an expert and respond
accordingly.

TIP: IF YOU DON'T KNOW THE TERM
Ask: "What is the engineering term for when I want to stop my app
from calling a broken API?"
Answer: "Circuit Breaker"
Then use that keyword in your actual prompt.

